We’re making a carrot cake which is very near to Chef Gigi Ramirez. Chef Gigi @gigibramirez joined The French Laundry pastry team in 2018 after a decade working for the Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts at various properties throughout the United States. She started as a chef de partie and is now a pastry sous chef, crediting her early childhood memories with informing her career path.

“The first time I made this cake was with my mom when I was seven years old. And it’s because of this experience that I wanted to become a pastry chef. I have the recipe memorized and it’s my go-to dessert; adding the citrus really brings out the flavors of the spices so that each slice is balanced nicely and full of carrot as well. So, a big shout out to her (also named Gigi) who lives in Guaynabo Puerto Rico, where I was born and raised. She is my biggest supporter. I grew up with her and my father telling me to find something that makes me happy. And I have.

After I graduated the CIA Hyde Park with both an Associate and a bachelor’s degree, I began working for chefs like Eddie Hales and Bashar Al Shamali who taught me the basics of baking pastry and helped me continue to grow. I found a love of plating desserts and further expressing my creativity through chocolate showpieces.

When I decided to take a leap of faith and focus on Michelin fine dining @_tfl_ Chef Elwyn Boyles mentored me about the restaurant’s philosophy and vision and helped me become a better cook. He also gave us the encouragement to explore our surroundings for inspiration.

I feel so lucky and have a smile on my face when I work with the pastry team to write the menus and share ideas. I hope that I am making an impact on our team and they too can learn from my experiences.

For Valentine's Day, we’re making a Pink Praline Tart with Chef Nick Bonamico, Pastry Chef at @bouchon_bakery in Yountville. He's been with us for 15 years, first in New York and now in Napa Valley, and has been been instrumental in elevating and evolving our bakeries.

During one of our menu meetings, I challenged our pastry team to recreate this famous tart from Lyon, France. It takes some patience, and it's a process, but it's a rewarding one. The French definition of a praline is a candied nut and in this case we use almonds. The pink coloring is traditional in Lyon.

The Pâte Sucrée recipe for the tart dough hails from the Bouchon Bakery cookbook (page 129); you can use the extra dough for another tart or to make cookies. 

We talk about mise en place, having everything in its place, and that includes both ingredients and tools. We recommend a straight rolling pin, and using rolling guides (both found @jbprincecompany). Look for a heart shaped tart ring and pink pralines online (though you can also candy your own). 

And remember...hearts are made to be broken 😉

This tart will be available on Valentine’s Day at Bouchon Bakery in #yountville

Pâte Sucrée recipe excerpted from Bouchon Bakery by Thomas Keller and Sebastian Rouxel (@artisan_books). Copyright © 2012.

TAK Room is back... By popular demand, I'll be showing you how to make our @takroomnyc Beef Wellington.

We've heard your requests and are sharing the recipe online (see link in Bio). Our rendition is made with short ribs which gives you the opportunity to make it ahead of time. We surround that with a mousse of black trumpet mushrooms and wrap it in brioche dough which is a nod to the great French Chef Jean-Louis Palladin. Remember, this dish is a process that requires planning and time. It's a new year, so set your cooking goals high. With patience, you'll get there!

TAK Room is back... By popular demand, I'll be showing you how to make our @takroomnyc Beef Wellington.

We've heard your requests and are sharing the recipe online (see link in Bio). Our rendition is made with short ribs which gives you the opportunity to make it ahead of time. We surround that with a mousse of black trumpet mushrooms and wrap it in brioche dough which is a nod to the great French Chef Jean-Louis Palladin. Remember, this dish is a process that requires planning and time. It's a new year, so set your cooking goals high. With patience, you'll get there!

We’re going to start by making a kale aioli, we'll move on to making the vegetable croquettes and then a cauliflower salad. It’s a dish from our cookbook @artisan_books THE FRENCH LAUNDRY, PER SE from @perseny Chef de Cuisine @coreydchow who was inspired by Per Se’s former Chef de Cuisine Eli Kaimeh who grew up eating Mediterranean food. 

This recipe is a kind of falafel made with ground winter vegetables seasoned with coriander, garlic, and parsley. They’re vegetarian and bound with chickpea flour, shaped into a quenelle, and fried till super crispy. Corey also makes these with only cauliflower, utilizing the entire vegetable, stem, and all. 

I can’t tell you how proud of the individuals who began this journey with me back in 1994 and those since -- who have had such a profound influence on our kitchens and dining room. And thank you, for taking the time to enjoy this moment of cooking with me. #thefrenchlaundryperse

Welcome to our new cookbook. I say "ours" because there were so many people involved in the making of this book. As with restaurants, it's not just about one person, it's about so many.

Some of you know how much I love eggs. Today I want to introduce you to one of my favorite dishes in the book; #TheFrenchLaundryPerSe - the Soft-Boiled Bantam Hen Egg with Shaved White Truffles. It’s simple and decadent. We cook the eggs, then hold them in beurre monté to keep them warm. The beurre monté also gives the eggs a beautiful sheen and additional flavor. We'll also make a creamed spinach béchamel and a sauce soubise as well.

You’ll find the recipe in THE FRENCH LAUNDRY, PER SE, written with @coreydchow, @_chefdavidbreeden, and their teams at @perseny and @_tfl_. Published by @artisan_books and available now wherever books are sold. For signed copies, visit thomaskeller.com/TheFrenchLaundryPerSeCookbook

node.title: Soft-Boiled Bantam Hen Egg with Shaved White Truffles

node.text:
We're making Angel Food Cake today in our R&D kitchen in Napa. A simple recipe that is very light and goes well with any berry or fruit. Here we are serving it with strawberry coulis and cream chantilly. Its roots go back to the Boston Cooking School and I believe Fanny Farmer gave it its name. For me, that recipe coincided with the advent of electric beaters and I remember my mom making frosting with hers - handing off one beater to me and one to my brother to lick off the frosting!

For all of you out there, this is my last Ode to TAK Room video. Thank you for your support and for conjuring up positive thoughts of good times together in our beloved restaurant. Thank you team @TAKRoomNYC for all that you brought to our hidden gem on the fifth floor.

node.title: Ode to TAK Room: Angel Food Cake

We're here in our Research & Development kitchen in Napa where all the recipes for @TAKRoomNYC were originally developed and today I am making a TAK Room classic: Eggplant Parmesan. This version is vegetarian and is topped with grated parmesan and then finished with breadcrumbs and basil buds. It's both nutritious and takes me back to my childhood when our family would eat this dish on special occasions.

TAK Room was a very important restaurant to me and I miss it every day.

node.title: Ode to TAK Room: Eggplant Parmesan

node.text:
One of my greatest food memories as a child was enjoying French onion dip that my mother would make - she'd open up a packet of onion soup mix, stir in the sour cream and serve it with a bag of chips. We recreated this at TAK Room and served it with our own potato chips.
.
This recipe is straightforward and you can make it a few days in advance using the TAK Room Buttermilk Dressing Base (see Highlights for the recipe in previous post). Remember when toasting the minced onions; slow and low is the way to go!
.
For those that enjoy a bit of decadence, I'll show you a variation that adds caviar.
.
I hope this conjures up memories for you too.

node.text:
I’ve just spent the past two days at @theculinaryinstituteofamerica meeting and speaking to the Class of 2021 receiving their degrees. It was a privilege, and I was inspired by their optimism and determination. 
.
Special thanks to Dr. Tim Ryan for bestowing me with this Honorary Doctorate. An extraordinary moment for me personally as I have no formal culinary education, no formal training; I began as a dishwasher. I learned by doing. I learned from watching others. And, I would say, I learned even more by making mistakes.
.
Graduates: Ask yourself today: what do you want? And what are you willing to do to get it? Then tomorrow, begin the journey. Continue to evolve. Be open to opportunities. On a daily basis, we adjust, adapt, and deliver to the best of our ability, to nourish and make an experience–a memory–for others. And we do this with great pride.  
.
I expect that I will see great things from all of you in the future. In your generation, you can make a difference: not just for yourself, but for those who will follow. 
.
Our profession needs you more than ever! Be bold. Be generous. And be happy! #Proud2bCIA #CIAHydePark [📷 by @twkeyes]

node.text: Chef Jean-Yves Piquet was one of our chef icons in America, teaching so many of us the meaning of precise craftsmanship, refinement and finesse. He had a huge impact on my career, not because I worked for him, but because I aspired to be as good as he was. His generation of French chefs helped lift America to the heights of cuisine in all areas. Jean was a unique and caring man, who at the least, climbed the mountain to attain respect and legacy in a profession that required determination and dedication. Heavy heart today knowing that you won’t be at our table in the future. Love you Chef!

node.text:
On this Father's Day, I find myself reflecting on the many meals I shared with my dad. Many took place at important transitions in my life. For all of us, food is often our companion during pivotal moments.⁣
⁣
A good way to celebrate our father figures is to cook for them. For me, my go to menu was BBQ chicken, mashed potatoes, collard greens with strawberry shortcake for dessert (in the @adhoc_addendum cookbook). But if you're not up for cooking this holiday, find meaning in whatever gesture works for you. It's the memories that count.

node.text:
Nutrition is always at the forefront of what we do; being able to add nutritional impact to our foods, and therefore to our bodies. We have partnered with @supplantcompany on the launch of Supplant™ sugars from fiber. A new blend of sugars found naturally in plant fiber,  Supplant™ is lower in calories, has a lower glycemic response, and is prebiotic, all with the same sweet taste as traditional cane sugar. Supplant™ sugars from fiber shares our commitment to environmental practices; this plant-based ingredient is made with upcycled agricultural crops that may otherwise be discarded. ⁣
.⁣
We invite you to join us this weekend in #Yountville for a complimentary sample of the Bouchon Bakery x Supplant™ sugars from fiber - Vanilla Ice Cream topped with @kellermannichocolate sprinkles and shortbread, all made with Supplant™. My mother Betty set an extraordinary example. Her attention to detail, the choices she made, the way she worked, and how she lived her life raising six children as a single mother has continued to shape me. 

Single mothers, working mothers, mothers across the country and around the world – this past year they have been challenged like never before. I’m so grateful for all of you, and for the amazing mothers in my own life who have taught me so much. #happymothersday

Thank you @michelinguide. This year has given us the opportunity to reflect on the individuals who together make @perseny the experience it is today. From former and current staff to our loyal guests, suppliers to farmers and small-business owners, each leave an indelible mark on our restaurant. Without you, none of this would be possible.⁣
⁣
With the reopening of our blue doors, we cannot help but consider the team members who are no longer working alongside us. The devastation wrought on our profession—from permanent restaurant closures to colleagues who have decided to leave the industry all together—is undeniable.⁣
⁣
Many challenges persist. But we are motivated by the perseverance of our peers and our city. As we forge a new path forward, we do so with the utmost gratitude for our community. We love NY! #AllinNYC #MICHELINguideNY  #MICHELINSTAR21
